  "text": "# Firefox Content Security Policy Enforcement Audit\n\n## Overview\nThe Firefox CSP enforcement infrastructure is implemented across several key files in the `dom/security/` directory and the interface is declared in `dom/interfaces/security/`.\n\n## Key Components Found:\n\n### 1. CSP Directive Parser: `nsCSPParser`\n**Files:** `dom/security/nsCSPParser.cpp` and `dom/security/nsCSPParser.h`\n\nThe `nsCSPParser` class implements the CSP specification parser, which tokenizes and parses CSP policy strings. The main entry point is the static method `nsCSPParser::parseContentSecurityPolicy()` which accepts a policy string, self URI, report-only flag, and CSP context. This parser follows a finite state machine approach based on the W3C CSP specification's source-list grammar.\n\n### 2. CSP Context Manager: `nsCSPContext`\n**Files:** `dom/security/nsCSPContext.cpp` and `dom/security/nsCSPContext.h`\n\nThe `nsCSPContext` class is the main CSP context that manages and enforces Content Security Policies. It implements the `nsIContentSecurityPolicy` interface and holds multiple `nsCSPPolicy` objects in its `mPolicies` array. Key responsibilities include:\n- Enforcing CSP directives\n- Handling inline script/style evaluation via `GetAllowsInline()` method\n- Reporting CSP violations\n- Managing violation event dispatching\n\n**Critical Method for Script-src Evaluation:** `nsCSPContext::GetAllowsInline()` (line 637 in nsCSPContext.cpp) performs script-src evaluation for inline scripts. This method checks whether inline scripts are allowed under the CSP policies, handling nonces, hashes, strict-dynamic, and other CSP mechanisms.\n\n### 3. CSP Utilities & Violation Reporting: `nsCSPUtils`\n**Files:** `dom/security/nsCSPUtils.cpp` and `dom/security/nsCSPUtils.h`\n\nThis module contains CSP utility functions including:\n- `CSP_LogLocalizedStr()` - Logs localized CSP violation messages\n- `CSP_LogMessage()` - Core message logging function\n- `CSP_LogStrMessage()` - String